title: Support asymmetric paddings in CUDA Conv kernel
body:
Support asymmetric padding in CUDA Conv kernel.

Problem: 
1) If pads are known at model load time (through `pad` attribute) and if they turn out to be asymmetric, we fallback to CPU EP (as CuDNN does not natively support asymmetric padding). This leads to poor performance for models containing such nodes. 
(https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/1961 https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2313 https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3221)

2) If pads have to be computed dynamically at Run() time (through `auto_pad` attribute) and if they turn out to be asymmetric, we make the pad symmetric and introduce noise which leads to output data not aligning with expected output values (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4488)

Solution:
Implement @joba01's idea (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3414#issuecomment-622040645) into the CUDA Conv kernel

Motivation:
Fixes https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/4488 https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3221 https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2313 and partially mitigates https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/1961 (the perf of YoloV3 improved by ~ 20%)

class GRU_Helper():
   def __init__(self, **params):  # type: (*Any) -> None
       # GRU Input Names
       X = str('X')
       W = str('W')
       R = str('R')
       B = str('B')
       H_0 = str('initial_h')
       LBR = str('linear_before_reset')
       number_of_gates = 3

       required_inputs = [X, W, R]
       for i in required_inputs:
           assert i in params, "Missing Required Input: {0}".format(i)

       self.num_directions = params[W].shape[0]

       if self.num_directions == 1:
           for k in params.keys():
               if k != X:
                   params[k] = np.squeeze(params[k], axis=0)

           hidden_size = params[R].shape[-1]
           batch_size = params[X].shape[1]

           b = params[B] if B in params else np.zeros(2 * number_of_gates * hidden_size)
           h_0 = params[H_0] if H_0 in params else np.zeros((batch_size, hidden_size))
           lbr = params[LBR] if LBR in params else 0

           self.X = params[X]
           self.W = params[W]
           self.R = params[R]
           self.B = b
           self.H_0 = h_0
           self.LBR = lbr

       else:
           raise NotImplementedError()

   def f(self, x):  # type: (np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray
       return 1 / (1 + np.exp(-x))

   def g(self, x):  # type: (np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray
       return np.tanh(x)

   def step(self):  # type: () -> Tuple[np.ndarray, np.ndarray]
       h_list = []
       [w_z, w_r, w_h] = np.split(self.W, 3)
       [r_z, r_r, r_h] = np.split(self.R, 3)
       [w_bz, w_br, w_bh, r_bz, r_br, r_bh] = np.split(self.B, 6)
       gates_w = np.transpose(np.concatenate((w_z, w_r)))
       gates_r = np.transpose(np.concatenate((r_z, r_r)))
       gates_b = np.add(np.concatenate((w_bz, w_br)), np.concatenate((r_bz, r_br)))

       H_t = self.H_0
       for x in np.split(self.X, self.X.shape[0], axis=0):
           gates = np.dot(x, gates_w) + np.dot(H_t, gates_r) + gates_b

           z, r = np.split(gates, 2, -1)

           h_default = self.g(np.dot(x, np.transpose(w_h)) + np.dot(r * H_t, np.transpose(r_h)) + w_bh + r_bh)

           H = (1 - z) * h + z * H_t
           h_list.append(H)
           H_t = H
       concatenated = np.concatenate(h_list)
       if self.num_directions == 1:
           output = np.expand_dims(concatenated, 1)
       return output, h_list[-1]

**Description**: This PR addresses a case where the thread pool may drop work if all of the work queues are full.  The PR fixes the bug and adds a stress-test.  The new test previously failed, but now passes.

**Motivation and Context**
While investigating an unrelated issue, I noticed that the thread pool may drop tasks when a burst of 1024+ tasks is submitted by a thread from inside the pool. Currently the only scenario where I can see this occurring is when the parallel executor is used with a model in which such a large number of nodes become eligible to run all at once.  This PR fixes the underlying issue and adds a test case for burst-submission of work.

When building with cmake with unit tests disabled (`-Donnxruntime_BUILD_UNIT_TESTS=OFF`), it is not possible to build with enabled training (`-Donnxruntime_ENABLE_TRAINING=ON`) because this unconditionally adds the `onnxruntime_training_runner` target, which requires the perf test sources.

**Urgency**
None. it can be trivially workarounded by implementing the solution suggested below.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Ubuntu 18.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.4.0
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): 7.5.0

**To Reproduce**
- Clone repository
- `mkdir build; cd build`
- `cmake .. -Donnxruntime_BUILD_UNIT_TESTS=OFF -Donnxruntime_ENABLE_TRAINING=ON`

**Solution**
The `TEST_SRC_DIR` variable is set on the top level `CMakeLists.txt` file.

title: Fix fusion tool for backward compatibility
ConvTranspose output shape incorrect when auto_pad attribute is set.
body:
**Describe the bug**
The [Onnx specification for ConvTranspose](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#ConvTranspose) states that only one of the attributes `auto_pad` and `padding` may be applied. Constructing a graph with `auto_pad='SAME_UPPER'` performs proper shape inference, however, onnxruntime produces an incorrect output as it assumes that `padding=[0, 0]` and overrides the auto_pad value.

**Urgency**
Medium priority, this should be causing issues for onnx graphs that use auto_pad for ConvTranspose operators.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Linux Ubuntu 18.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.4.0
- Python version: 3.7.7
- Visual Studio version (if applicable):
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source):
- CUDA/cuDNN version:
- GPU model and memory:

**To Reproduce**
```
import onnx
from onnx import helper, TensorProto
import onnxruntime.backend
import numpy as np

x_shape = [1, 1, 5, 5]
w_shape = [1, 1, 3, 3]
y_shape = [1, 1, 9, 9]
node = helper.make_node(
    'ConvTranspose',
    inputs=['x', 'W'],
    outputs=['y'],
    kernel_shape=[3, 3],
    strides=[2, 2],
    dilations=[1, 1],
    auto_pad='SAME_UPPER')

graph = helper.make_graph(
    [node],
    'convtranspose_test',
    inputs=[helper.make_tensor_value_info("x", TensorProto.FLOAT, list(x_shape)), helper.make_tensor_value_info("W", TensorProto.FLOAT, list(w_shape))],
    outputs=[helper.make_tensor_value_info("y", TensorProto.FLOAT, list(y_shape))])

model = helper.make_model(graph, producer_name='convtranspose_test')

rep = onnxruntime.backend.prepare(model, 'CPU')
x = np.random.uniform(size=x_shape).astype('float32')
W = np.random.uniform(size=w_shape).astype('float32')
ord_out = rep.run([x, W])[0]
print(ord_out.shape)
```
**Expected behavior**
The output shape should be `[1, 1, 9, 9]` however running the above script produces a shape of `[1, 1, 11, 11]`, which would be the expected shape if we had set the padding attribute to `[0, 0]`. The output of onnxruntime directly contradicts the onnx graph we constructed.

title: Revert "Remove code which is not thread-safe. (#4454)"

labels.name: core runtime
labels.description: issues related to core runtime

body:
This reverts commit 5222b2c6c0366033aaa78b95b2a0a49984984203.

We still need to log how much memory allocated for static initializers, static activation, and dynamic activation. The first commit brings that functionality back. This PR also make it thread-safe (it was removed because it wasn't thread-safe) by introducing a mutex in ExecutionFrame in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/4712/commits/4f163d23779399ad731b52e6f15a3d0b77e2c2d9 and some extra safety measures in https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/4712/commits/78f8c518baf92b0ee01ba589e03a6594d25cb4ef.

From my preliminary investigation, the thread-safe is required because dynamic memory is logged in ExecutionFrame
```
  // Size of virtual memory allocated during kernel execution (i.e., inside a kernel,
  // we may allocate some memory for its outputs, if not planned.).
  // This field is not physical memory size.
  std::unordered_map<std::string, size_t> dynamic_activation_memory_sizes_in_byte_;
```
and parallel executor can launch multiple kernels at the same time (kernels can allocates dynamic memory at the same time).

With this PR and `--ort_log_severity 1`, we get information like below:
```
[Memory] SessionStateInitializer statically allocates 2386034688 bytes for Cuda
[Memory] SessionStateInitializer statically allocates 49152 bytes for Cpu
```
for constants and initializers and
```
[Memory] ExecutionFrame statically allocates 503553536 bytes for Cuda
[Memory] ExecutionFrame statically allocates 128 bytes for CudaPinned
[Memory] ExecutionFrame dynamically allocates 384 bytes for CudaPinned
[Memory] ExecutionFrame dynamically allocates 7296 bytes for Cuda
```
for activations.

title: Add a generic collection of session configurations to the SessionOptions
body:
**Description**: 
Add generic configurations for session options

**Motivation and Context**
Right now in order to change some setting within an inference sessions, we will need to either
- Use ORTAPI, add entry if necessary, (will bloat the c/cxx_api)
- Use environmental variables, (not really work for some environments, such as mobile)
- Hardcode the settings (not really applicable to end users )

This proposal is to add a single function OrtApis::SetSessionConfiguration to add different configurations for the inference session
- Exposing new options will not require updating the ORTAPI any more
- Use a std::unordered_map as the collection of the configurations
- Define an enum as the config key, and a std::string as the config value, the consumer of the config will be responsible to parse the string
- EP will still using constructor for EP specific configurations
